'''Angus Fraser James Gunn''' (born 22 January 1996) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for {{English football updater|NottingF}} club [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

Gunn began his career at his hometown club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], before joining [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2011, signing his first professional contract in 2013. After spending the [[2017–18 Norwich City F.C. season|2017–18]] season on loan at Norwich, Gunn signed for [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in the summer of 2018, for a transfer fee of £13.5 million. After a return to the Championship with [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] for the [[2020–21 Stoke City F.C. season|2020–21 season]], he returned to Norwich on a permanent basis following their promotion back to the [[Premier League]].

Gunn represented England at [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] level but declared for Scotland in March 2023. He made his senior debut later that month, and was part of Scotland's squad at [[UEFA Euro 2024]].

==Early life==
Gunn was born in [[Norwich]], Norfolk,<ref name=11v11>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/angus-gunn-239276/ |title=Angus Gunn |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref> to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]'s former goalkeeper and manager [[Bryan Gunn|Bryan]] and 
artist [[Susan Gunn]].<ref name=family>{{cite news |first=Scott |last=McDermott |title=Bryan Gunn will support his son Angus even if England's No1 prospect dumps Scotland in the World Cup |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/bryan-gunn-support-son-angus-6488047 |newspaper=Daily Record |location=Glasgow |date=21 September 2015 |access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref> His father is originally from [[Thurso]] in the far north of Scotland.<ref name=family/> He has two sisters, Francesca, Melissa; Francesca died four years before he was born.<ref name="author2">{{Cite news |last=Shaw |first=Phil |date=25 October 2006 |title=Author of a different kind of football book: Fighting back with the Gunns |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/author-of-a-different-kind-of-football-book-fighting-back-with-the-gunns-421437.html |access-date=13 May 2011 |work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>

Gunn attended Alpington Primary School and [[Framingham Earl High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Freezer |first1=David |title=Profile: Norwich City legend Bryan Gunn believed son Angus had "opportunity to be a top goalkeeper" with Manchester City |url=https://www.pinkun.com/norwich-city/profile-norwich-city-legend-bryan-gunn-believed-son-angus-had-opportunity-to-be-a-top-goalkeeper-with-manchester-city-1-5049773 |website=Pink Un |access-date=21 October 2020 |archive-date=23 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201023022507/https://www.pinkun.com/norwich-city/profile-norwich-city-legend-bryan-gunn-believed-son-angus-had-opportunity-to-be-a-top-goalkeeper-with-manchester-city-1-5049773 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Club career==
===Manchester City===
Gunn began his career at his hometown club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], before moving to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2011, for which a tribunal decided Manchester City had to pay £250,000.<ref name="Norwich loan">{{cite news |title=Angus Gunn: Manchester City keeper rejoins Norwich City on season-long loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40171108 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2017 |access-date=20 July 2017}}</ref> He signed a three-year professional contract in June 2013.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Bailey |title=Angus Gunn is Manchester City's newest professional keeper – but he still holds Norwich City dear |url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/norwich-city/angus-gunn-is-manchester-city-s-newest-professional-keeper-but-he-still-holds-norwich-city-dear-1-2241920 |newspaper=Eastern Daily Press |location=Norwich |date=19 June 2013 |access-date=10 August 2017}}</ref> He was named on the [[Substitute (association football)|substitutes bench]] on a number of occasions throughout the [[2016–17 Manchester City F.C. season|2016–17 season]], but did not play for Manchester City that season.<ref name="Norwich loan"/>

For the [[2017–18 Norwich City F.C. season|2017–18 season]], Gunn was [[Loan (sports)|loaned]] back to Norwich of the [[EFL Championship]].<ref name="Norwich loan"/> He made his first-team debut in Norwich's first match of the season, away to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref name=sb1718/> He got his first professional football clean sheet on 16 August 2017, in a 2–0 home win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Carrow Road]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40871609 |title=Norwich City 2–0 Queens Park Rangers |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 August 2017 |access-date=10 September 2017}}</ref> He would ultimately be the only player to be ever present for Norwich in the league during the season, also being ever present in the [[FA Cup]] and making three appearances in the [[EFL Cup]]. At the end of the season, Norwich fans voted him third in the Player of the Season vote behind [[James Maddison]] and [[Grant Hanley]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2018/april/maddison-pots/ |title=James Maddison voted Player of the Season|publisher=canaries.co.uk |date=28 April 2018 |access-date=10 June 2018}}</ref>

===Southampton===
Gunn joined [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] in July 2018, signing a five-year deal with the club,<ref>{{cite news |title=Gunn completes Saints move |url=https://southamptonfc.com/news/2018-07-10/announcement-southampton-manchester-city-angus-gunn-transfer |website=saintsfc |location=Norwich |date=10 July 2018 |access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref> for a fee estimated at £13.5 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stone |first1=Simon |title=Angus Gunn: Southampton complete signing of £13.5m deal for Man City goalkeeper |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44771592 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=10 July 2018 |date=10 July 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 28 August 2018 in an [[EFL Cup]] tie against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], and his [[Premier League]] debut on 2 January 2019, making several vital saves and keeping a clean sheet and earning the man of the match award in a 0–0 draw against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Emons |first1=Michael |title=Chelsea 0–0 Southampton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46682779 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=3 January 2019 |date=2 January 2019}}</ref>

====Stoke City (loan)====
In October 2020 Gunn joined [[EFL Championship]] side [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] on loan for the [[2020–21 Stoke City F.C. season|2020–21 season]] as a replacement for the departing [[Jack Butland]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Potters land Gunn |url=https://www.stokecityfc.com/news/2020/october/Potters-land-Gunn/ |website=Stoke City |date=16 October 2020 |access-date=16 October 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Jack Butland: Crystal Palace sign Stoke goalkeeper after transfer deadline |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54578568 |access-date=16 October 2020}}</ref> Gunn made his debut on 27 October 2020 against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] coming on as a half time substitute for the injured [[Adam Davies (footballer, born 1992)|Adam Davies]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Swansea City 2–0 Stoke City |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54610090 |access-date=11 May 2021}}</ref> He kept his place for the next three matches before he suffered an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stoke City hit by Angus Gunn injury shock |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stoke-city-angus-gunn-injury-4717680 |website=Stoke Sentinel |date=19 November 2020 |access-date=11 May 2021}}</ref> [[Josef Bursik (footballer)|Josef Bursik]] took his place in goal until both Gunn and Davies returned to fitness in January.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boost for Stoke City as two senior keepers return to training on same day |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/stoke-city-davies-gunn-injury-4889279 |website=Stoke Sentinel |date=14 January 2021 |access-date=11 May 2021}}</ref> Gunn made 15 appearances for Stoke until his season was ended by a foot injury in April 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=Key man returns for Stoke City, Gunn heads back to Southampton, defender set for surgery |url=https://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/stoke-angus-gunn-transfer-southampton-5362334 |website=Stoke Sentinel |date=30 April 2021 |access-date=11 May 2021}}</ref>

===Norwich City===
On 23 June 2021, Gunn made a permanent return to Norwich, for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.southamptonfc.com/news/2021-06-23/angus-gunn-permanent-deal-southampton-norwich-city | title=Gunn completes Norwich City move | publisher=Southampton FC | date=23 June 2021 | access-date=23 June 2021}}</ref> On 28 April 2025, it was announced that Gunn would leave the club at the end of the season, when his contract expired.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-04-28 |title=Angus Gunn: Scotland goalkeeper to leave Norwich City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cp8v6zpyv3po |access-date=2025-04-28 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

===Nottingham Forest===
On 6 August 2025, Gunn joined [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on a one-year deal.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-08-06 |title=Scotland keeper Gunn joins Forest after contract expiry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cy7y03m1v43o |access-date=2025-08-06 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He made his Forest debut on 1 February 2026 in a Premier League match against Crystal Palace at the City Ground as a half-time replacement for the injured [[Matz Sels]].

==International career==
===England===
[[File:France - England U19, 20150331 06.JPG|thumb|right|Gunn playing for the [[England national under-19 football team|England under-19 team]] in 2015]]
Despite his father Bryan representing Scotland at international level, Angus represented England at various youth levels.<ref name="author">{{Cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/author-of-a-different-kind-of-football-book-fighting-back-with-the-gunns-421437.html |work = [[The Independent]] | title = Author of a different kind of football book: Fighting back with the Gunns | first = Phil| last = Shaw| date =25 October 2006 | access-date =13 May 2011}}</ref> Gunn received his first call up to the [[England national football team|England national team]] in November 2017 for a [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], after [[Jack Butland]] withdrew from the squad with an injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Angus Gunn: Man City goalkeeper called up by England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41950285 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 November 2017 |access-date=11 November 2017}}</ref> In March 2018, Gunn was offered the opportunity by [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] manager [[Alex McLeish]] to switch allegiances to Scotland, but decided to stay with the England national team,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edp24.co.uk/sport/norwich-city/ex-canaries-keeper-gunn-refuses-to-switch-international-loyalties-1-6317827|title=Scotland boss fails with international advances for ex-City 'keeper Gunn|first=Connor|last=Southwell|website=Eastern Daily Press |date=11 October 2019 }}</ref> and was called up by [[Gareth Southgate]] to their training camp ahead of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Angus Gunn drafted into England World Cup plans |url=https://readnorwich.com/2018/05/18/angus-gunn-drafted-into-england-world-cup-plans/ |website=Read Norwich |date=17 May 2018 |access-date=17 June 2018}}</ref>

===Scotland===
Gunn switched his international allegiance to Scotland in March 2023,<ref name="nationalswitch">{{cite news |title=Angus Gunn: Norwich City goalkeeper commits international future to Scotland |website=[[BBC Sport]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64932621}}</ref> and was selected in their squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying]] matches that month.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64938719 |title=Scotland : Zander Clark & Angus Gunn named in squad for Spain & Cyprus games |website=BBC Sport |date=14 March 2023 |accessdate=14 March 2023}}</ref>

He made his debut on 25 March against [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] at [[Hampden Park]], keeping a clean sheet in a 3–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glasgowlive.co.uk/sport/scotland-3-cyprus-0-john-26558716|title=Scotland 3 Cyprus 0 as John McGinn breaks records and Angus Gunn debuts in Hampden victory|website=Glasgow Live|date=25 March 2023|accessdate=25 March 2023}}</ref> Three days later, Gunn recorded his second clean sheet in his second appearance for Scotland as they defeated [[Spain national football team|Spain]] 2–0 to go top of [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying Group A|Group A]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65022207|title=Scotland 2-0 Spain: Steve Clarke's side earn consecutive Euro 2024 qualification wins|date=28 March 2023|access-date=15 June 2024|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Overall, Gunn made six appearances for Scotland during Euro 2024 qualification, keeping four clean sheets as the Scots reached a second consecutive European Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2024/june/11/all-the-efl-players-at-euro-2024/|title=All the EFL players at Euro 2024|date=11 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=EFL}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Gunn was named in Scotland's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] finals in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> A week later, he started the opening match of the tournament, where he was beaten five times as Scotland lost 5–1 to hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in Munich.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> He went on to start against both [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1-1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref> and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref>

